                        "elaphron tes thlipseos) is preparing for us an eternal weight of glory (aionion baros "
                        "doxes) beyond all comparison' (4:17). The Hebrew word kavod means both 'glory' and "
                        "'heaviness' -- Paul exploits this by contrasting the 'lightness' of affliction with "
                        "the 'weight' of glory. Present suffering is feather-light; coming glory is infinitely "
                        "heavy. The chapter closes with the epistemological key to the entire passage: 'we look "
                        "not to the things that are seen but to the things that are unseen. For the things that "
                        "are seen are transient (proskaira), but the things that are unseen are eternal (aionia)' "
                        "(4:18). The unseen realm -- the domain of the divine council, the throne room of God, "
                        "the reality where Christ sits at the Father's right hand -- is the permanent reality. "
                        "The visible world governed by the god of this age is passing away. Faith is training "
                        "the eyes to see the unseen."
