                        "represents a sovereign in territory that is not yet under direct control. Believers "
                        "represent Christ's kingdom within the domain of the god of this age, making the appeal: "
                        "'be reconciled to God.' The chapter climaxes with the great exchange: 'For our sake he "
                        "made him to be sin (hamartian) who knew no sin, so that in him we might become the "
                        "righteousness of God (dikaiosyne theou)' (5:21). The sinless Christ absorbs the sin-"
